<Document>
<name>Bay of Kotor &amp; Lovćen Serpentine</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Bay of Kotor &amp; Lovćen Serpentine</h2><p><i>Montenegro · Kotor to Cetinje to Budva via the old Austrian road</i></p><p><b>25 numbered hairpins climbing 900 m up a vertical wall above Europe's southernmost fjord.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>28 km (17 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs with stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (winter snow on Lovćen)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Single-lane in places on the serpentine, blind hairpins, no guardrails on outer edges, summer crowds in Kotor</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>78</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Bay of Kotor is sometimes called 'Europe's southernmost fjord' — geologically it's a flooded river canyon, not a true glacial fjord, but the visual effect is the same: a deep blue-water inlet ringed by limestone walls a thousand metres high. Kotor itself is a UNESCO walled medieval town. Behind it, the Lovćen serpentine — 25 numbered hairpins built by the Austro-Hungarians in the 1880s — climbs the back wall of the bay in 8 km and 900 m. The road continues across Lovćen NP to Cetinje, the historic royal capital, then descends to Budva on the Adriatic coast. From the upper hairpins the entire bay opens below you like a relief map.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Kotor old town</b> — UNESCO walled medieval town (12th–14th centuries) at the head of the bay. Climb the city walls to St John's fortress (1,350 steps) for the classic view down into the bay.</li><li><b>Krstac viewpoint</b> — Halfway up the serpentine — pull off and look down on Kotor, the bay, and (in clear weather) all the way to the Adriatic. Best photo: late afternoon.</li><li><b>Njeguši</b> — Mountain village famous for pršut (smoked ham) and cheese, both cured in the village's specific air conditions. Roadside stalls and a single restaurant; the view from the road into the bay is memorable.</li><li><b>Njegoš Mausoleum (Lovćen summit)</b> — 1,657 m. Tomb of Petar II Petrović-Njegoš (1813–51), Montenegro's prince-bishop and national poet. 461 steps up to the marble entrance; the panorama from the platform behind covers four countries.</li><li><b>Cetinje</b> — Historic royal capital of the independent Kingdom of Montenegro (1878–1918). Sleepy provincial town now, but the embassies of the great powers are all still there as buildings, lining the main street.</li><li><b>Budva</b> — Walled coastal town, Mediterranean beach resort, founded 2,500 years ago. Sveti Stefan, the postcard hotel-island just south, is currently in legal limbo and not always accessible.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
